April 01, 2024 15:55 ET (19:55 GMT)
title: ICE Futures U.S. Sugar 16 Settlements - Apr 1

text:
The latest Market Talks covering Commodities. Published exclusively on Dow Jones Newswires throughout the day.

1149 ET - Coffee prices rise 1% to $2.06 a pound, gaining support from poor robusta coffee bean production in heat wave-stricken Vietnam. While production levels for the 2024-25 season are expected to provide a surplus, short-term prices could rise further to $2.10-$2.20 a pound due to adverse weather and further financial inflows, among other factors, Citi says. The U.S. bank hikes its 2024 average price expectation around 10% to $1.94 a pound. "To the extent robusta supply stays tight and consumption rebounds in 2025, the risk skew for higher coffee prices appears to have increased in [the second quarter]," Citi analysts say in a note. Elsewhere on the commodities market, cocoa futures fall 0.7% to $9,461 a ton, while sugar rises 0.6% to 22 cents a pound. (joseph.hoppe@wsj.com)

1100 ET - U.S. natural gas futures move lower as a weekly inventory report lands close to expectations. Natural gas in underground storage decreased by 37 billion cubic feet in the week ended March 29 to 2,259 Bcf, which was 422 Bcf or 23% above the year-earlier level and 633 Bcf or 38.9% above the five-year average, the EIA reports. Analysts in a Wall Street Journal survey had predicted a withdrawal of 40 Bcf. It was the second consecutive above-average weekly draw as the November-March heating season came to a close. Storage is rebuilt over the summer for the next winter's demand. "It appears the end of October estimate for supplies is still a whopping 4.1 trillion cubic feet," Phil Flynn of the Price Futures Group says in a report. Natural gas for May delivery is off 1.9% at $1.806/mmBtu. (anthony.harrup@wsj.com)

1013 ET - CME livestock futures start the day lower, with live cattle down 0.1% and lean hogs dropping by 0.6%. Export sales reported by the USDA this morning were mixed, with sales of beef up from last week while pork sales pulled back. Beef sales totaled 18,700 metric tons--up 48%, while pork sales were reported at 28,700 tons, down 48%. Cattle futures have been rangebound in recent trading, while hogs have been on the ascent. (kirk.maltais@wsj.com)

1002 ET - A drier and warmer forecast for the U.S. Corn Belt heading into this weekend may allow farmers the window of time they need to get crops in the ground early, says AgResource in a note. The U.S. growing season typically begins in April and isn't finished until late May. "The choppy nature of the marketplace will be unchanged until 2024's weather/supply story emerges," says the firm, which adds that the 'odds of a timely planting season are on the rise. Corn is up 0.4%, soybeans are off 0.5%, and wheat loses 0.5%. (kirk.maltais@wsj.com; @kirkmaltais)

0946 ET - U.S data weighs down the dollar, as jobless claims come in higher than expected and the trade deficit widens. The WSJ Dollar Index is down 0.2% and the greenback weakens 0.4% versus the euro and 0.7% against the Australian dollar. Bank of America's Athanasios Vamvakidis says in a note that he sticks to an outlook of weaker dollar by year end. The forecast "relies on three assumptions, but with risks it could take longer: slower US growth; Fed cuts this year; the USD is overvalued." March payrolls tomorrow are likely to have an impact on FX trade. (paulo.trevisani@wsj.com; @ptrevisani)

0943 ET - The rally in crude prices puts $93-$95 a barrel for Brent within reach given the extension of OPEC+ output cuts and perceived risks of Iranian supply being affected by the Mideast conflict, although strong resistance at that level is likely as it could lead producers to sell forward and speculators to take some profits, analysts at Citi say in a note. "An actual disruption to Iran's oil supply could take us to a bull case (with high prices sustaining an average $90 by 3Q24)," they say. Citi remains bearish for 2025, seeing demand growth slowing to less than 1 million barrels a day as the post-pandemic jet-fuel recovery loses momentum and electric vehicle take-up becomes more visible. "We continue to see an inflection from a bull market to a bearish one by mid-year," they add. (anthony.harrup@wsj.com)

0904 ET - U.S. natural gas futures are steady as the market watches for the EIA's weekly storage report, which is expected to show an above-average draw on inventories for last week. "We are not expecting much reaction to today's EIA storage since the data tends to approximate average street ideas during the shoulder period as the weather factor diminishes," Ritterbusch says in a note. "But we also believe that our expected 35 Bcf narrowing in the storage surplus will be the start of a trend that could extend into next month." Analysts in a Wall Street Journal survey predict on average a 40 Bcf draw on storage. Natural gas for May delivery is down a penny or 0.4% at $1.833/mmBtu. (anthony.harrup@wsj.com)

0848 ET - Capital Economics predicts that oil prices, currently trading at five-month highs, will retreat in the second half of the year and beyond with OPEC+ likely to starting unwinding its output cuts over concerns about losing market share. "This will more than cover the modest strengthening in demand we expect as advanced economies start loosening monetary policy," analysts say in a report. They attribute this year's rally to Ukraine's strikes on Russian energy infrastructure and the conflict in the Middle East, along with the OPEC+ cuts. "We forecast that the price of Brent will have slipped to $60 per barrel by end-2026, from $89 at the time of writing," they add. June Brent is off 0.2% at $89.15, and WTI for May delivery is down 0.3% at $85.15. (anthony.harrup@wsj.com)

0629 ET - Palm oil prices closed lower in Asian trade, reversing earlier gains. Prices were marginally lower on weaker crude oil prices and likely profit-taking, given the recent price rally in palm oil, said David Ng, a trader at Kuala Lumpur-based proprietary trading company Iceberg X. Ng pegs support for CPO futures at MYR4,300 and resistance at MYR4,500. The Bursa Malaysia Derivatives contract for June delivery closed MYR10 lower at MYR4,397 a ton. (kimberley.kao@wsj.com)

0616 ET - Metal prices are mixed, with copper pulling ahead but gold futures slipping 0.1% to $2,312.6 a troy ounce. The precious metal has, however, rallied 3.3% over the last week and 12% in the year to date, following the Federal Reserve's reiteration of rate cuts being more than likely this year, SP Angel analysts say in a note. Traders are now pricing in two interest-rate cuts this year, SP Angel says. Elsewhere, copper rises 0.8% to $9,370.5 a metric ton, and 5.6% in the last week alone as manufacturing data improves and supply constraints persist, SP Angel says. The move caught the market by surprise, likely reflecting some short covering and momentum fund inflow--but longer-term demand prospects are improving, with U.S. manufacturing showing a rebound from a sustained downtrend, SP Angel says. (joseph.hoppe@wsj.com)

0412 ET - Gold prices may have further room to run in the medium term, OCBC foreign-exchange strategist Christopher Wong says in a note. The precious metal's recent price rally has brought gains this year to more than 11%. While the analyst thinks a near-term pullback is possible, given the rapid run-up, he maintains a bullish outlook on gold prices. Wong cites factors such as expectations of a global easing cycle, central banks' continued purchases of gold and a play-up of the precious metal's role as a geopolitical hedge. Spot gold is 0.3% lower at $2,293.38/oz after hitting a new record. (tracy.qu@wsj.com)

0354 ET - Base metals rise, benefiting from the continued risk-on appetite that gripped markets earlier this week. Aluminum rises 0.5% to $2,451.5 a ton, while copper gains 0.55% to $9,346.5 a ton. Speculative activity on the LME has surged, which--combined with expectations of relaxed monetary policy outlook in Europe--has sent metal prices to their highest levels in several months, Daria Efanova, head of research at Sucden Financial, says. Gold futures rise 1% to $2,316.9 a troy ounce while LBMA silver rises 2.3% to $26.25 an ounce. "We expect the forthcoming months to be favorable for precious metals, given the potential onset of monetary easing by major central banks and the increasing uncertainty surrounding the outcome of the U.S. elections," Efanova says in a note. (joseph.hoppe@wsj.com)

(END) Dow Jones Newswires

title: ICE White Sugar Futures Prices

text:
By Joe Hoppe

A roundup of key agricultural commodity markets for the week April 2 - April 5 by Dow Jones Newswires in Barcelona.

GRAINS & OILSEEDS:

The macro mood is mixed with the dollar staying strong ahead of this week's important U.S. job reports, a bearish headwind for agriculture futures.

The U.S. dollar has strengthened over the last week, posing a particular problem for the oilseed complex and worsening export prospects, given the weaker Chinese yuan and Brazilian real.

South American weather looks mixed, and while Argentina's weather has been favorably dry increased rainfall is forecast, which could slow down harvest progress, Peak Trading analysts said in a note. April is also a critical month for both the Brazilian second corn crop and the risky U.S. spring planting weeks, making price seasonals over the month traditionally bullish.

Elsewhere, weather forecasts across most of the U.S. Midwest are warm and rainy. Early rains are good for ground moisture, especially for the drought-stricken states in the northern plains, but could prevent planting if they persist into late April and early May, Peak Trading said.

The week will see the release of several important U.S. employment datasets, including payroll processing firm ADP's jobs report on Wednesday, and non-farm payrolls and unemployment data on Friday. Commodity markets would benefit from weakness in the data as they would undermine the dollar's strength, Peak said.

Friday's commitment of traders report indicated hedge funds have covered short positions and added new long positions across soybeans, bean oil and sugar last week, including buying grains last Thursday on the U.S. Department of Agriculture's supportive statistics for stocks and acreages.

Chicago wheat futures are 0.7% down at $5.61 a bushel on Tuesday, while corn is down 0.1% at $4.35 a bushel. Soybean prices are 1% up at $11.98 a bushel.

SOFT COMMODITIES:

Cocoa prices remain at record highs, having more than doubled since the start of the year and risen 3.1% in the last week alone. This rally is being pushed by a global supply crunch, Rabobank analysts said in a note.

BMI Research, a unit of Fitch Solutions, said cocoa prices rose 20% last week alone, and as of Tuesday on a year to date basis, cocoa is up 136%. On March 25, the Ghana Cocoa Board said the domestic harvest in 2023-2024 could be between 422,500 tons and 425,000 tons, the lowest output in more than two decades in the world's second largest producer.

Elsewhere, coffee futures have made gains as concerns about falling output from the Vietnamese robusta harvest continued to provide upward support for arabica prices. On March 26, Vietnam's Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development said output could fall to a four-season low as El Nino-related below-average rainfall and moisture continue to hit producers, BMI said.

Cocoa is down 2.3% at $9,888 a metric ton, while sugar is 1% down at 22.5 cents a pound on Tuesday. Coffee is up 1.4% at $1.94 a pound.

Write to Joe Hoppe at joseph.hoppe@wsj.com

(END) Dow Jones Newswires

text:
AB Foods' shares rise 9.6%, leading the FTSE 100 index, after the British conglomerate said it expects a significant growth in profit for the full year and raised its dividend payout. The group's retail arm Primark reported an adjusted operating profit jump of 46% to GBP508 million, and expects its operating margin to improve in the second half compared with 11.3% in the first. The following is a selection of analyst comments.

AB Foods Serves Up Dividend, Profit Surprises After Strong Performance

0722 GMT - AB Foods delivered a better-than-expected first-half performance, with Primark, grocery and ingredients operating margins ahead of expectations, RBC Capital Markets analysts Richard Chamberlain and Manjari Dhar write in a note. The conglomerate's 1H sales were in line with RBC's estimate, while adjusted operating profit of GBP951 million beat RBC's expectations of GBP823 million. Adjusted pretax profit was also ahead of views at GBP911 million compared withGBP818 million, and the dividend surprised at 20.7 pence versus RBC's forecast of 15.0 pence. The analysts expect further healthy sales trends at fashion retailer Primark in the short term and continuing recovery for store-based retailing, with a strong margin improvement ahead. Shares are up 7.2%, and 31% on a 12-month basis. (michael.susin@wsj.com)

AB Foods' Primark Margins Likely to Boost Shareholder Returns

0802 GMT - AB Foods' 1H performance was significantly ahead of market expectations driven by a jump in profit margins at its retail arm Primark, ensuring the potential for further shareholder returns, Liberum analysts Anubhav Malhotra and Wayne Brown say in a note. "Primark's store expansion program, further margin potential, and return on investments into capacity expansion in food should combine to deliver double-digit shareholder returns, including 5%-6% via dividends and buybacks over the medium term," they say. Primark's guidance for full year was upgraded as 2H margins are expected to be slightly above the 11.3% in 1H, the analysts add. Shares are up 8.9%, leading the FTSE 100 index. (michael.susin@wsj.com)

AB Foods' Primark Is Taking Market Share With Improved Offering

1038 GMT - AB Foods' first half was impressive, with strength across all areas and Primark particularly delivering a stunning performance, suggesting its value offering is resonating with cost-conscious consumers, AJ Bell investment director Russ Mould writes in a note. AB Foods' retail arm could have found the middle ground between its "Primarni" past--designer-inspired clothes at cheap prices--and providing better quality apparel at still affordable prices, therefore taking market share from rivals, Mould notes. "The company's strong balance sheet and diversified model...put the [it] in an enviable position to both reward shareholders and invest in further expansion in the business," Mould says. Shares are up 9.4%, leading the FTSE 100 risers. (michael.susin@wsj.com)

AB Foods Earnings Reflect Postpandemic Normalization Trends

1428 GMT - AB Foods reported a robust 1H with broad-based improvement across its portfolio despite Primark's volume remaining challenged, Barclays analysts Warren Ackerman and Patrick Folan say. The British conglomerate's standout figures were the 39% increase in adjusted operating profit and 46% rise in adjusted EPS, the analysts highlight. Despite the focus on Primark's margin beat, the strength of grocery, ingredients and sugar businesses was equally impressive, they say in a note. "Overall the results show a clear normalization of trends after the Covid years, supply chain challenges and inflation headwinds and the bounce back in profitability is a testament to the resilience of AB Foods' business model which some had questioned," they add. Barclays lifts the price target on the stock to GBP27 from GBP24. Shares are up 9.6%, and up 34% on a 12-month basis. (michael.susin@wsj.com)

(END) Dow Jones Newswires

text:
By Joe Hoppe

A roundup of key agricultural commodity markets for the week April 8-12 by Dow Jones Newswires in Barcelona.

GRAINS & OILSEEDS:

The macro mood is mixed with the dollar keeping relatively strong ahead of this week's U.S. CPI inflation data and Fed meeting minutes, a bearish headwind for agriculture futures.

The U.S. dollar has broadly retained its strength over the past week on firmer data, with bond yields and interest rates drifting higher and crucial commodities currencies like the Chinese yuan and the Brazilian real weak against the greenback.

South American weather looks good with no major threats, as Brazil enters its final stages of the soybean harvest and Argentina's harvest begins to ramp up into mid-April and early May, Peak Trading analysts said in a note. April is also a critical month for both the Brazilian second corn crop and the risky U.S. spring planting weeks, making price seasonals over the month traditionally bullish.

Elsewhere, temperatures are warming up in the U.S., which helps planting accelerate across the Midwest in the upcoming important planting weeks, Peak Trading said.

The week will see the release of U.S. CPI inflation data and Fed meeting minutes on Wednesday, followed by the European Central Bank policy decision and U.S. producer price index inflation data on Thursday, all of which will prompt plenty of dollar volatility, Peak said.

Friday's commitment of traders report indicated hedge funds bought hogs, sugar and cocoa, and sold corn and soybean meal, with funds having massive short bets in U.S. wheat markets.

Chicago wheat futures are 0.6% up at $5.71 a bushel on Monday, while corn is up 0.2% at $4.35 a bushel. Soybean prices are 0.1% up at $11.86 a bushel.

SOFT COMMODITIES:

Cocoa prices remain at record highs, though its rally appears to have slowed. The crop's price has more than doubled since the start of the year and risen 2.5% in the past week alone. The monthslong surge has been pushed by supply-side challenges in West Africa, where 70% of global cocoa is produced.

Friday's commitment of traders report showed the cocoa net long was cut to a fresh one-year low at 19,700 contracts, down 72% since January, while weather concerns in Brazil and Vietnam drove an increase in Arabica coffee net longs to a two-year high at 57,300 contracts, said Saxobank's head of commodity strategy, Ole Hansen, in a note.

The sugar situation has improved as the production outlook for India has recovered, so for now the focus for soft commodities is primarily on cocoa and coffee--especially robusta coffee, as primary producer Vietnam's current heatwave has raised concerns as production suffers, Hansen told Dow Jones Newswires.

Cocoa is up 5.7% at $10,350 a metric ton, while sugar is 1.3% down at 22 cents a pound on Monday. Coffee is down 0.7% at $2.11 a pound.

Write to Joe Hoppe at joseph.hoppe@wsj.com

(END) Dow Jones Newswires

April 10, 2024 15:55 ET (19:55 GMT)
title: ICE Futures U.S. Sugar 16 Settlements - Apr 10
ICE Futures U.S. Sugar 16 Close - Apr 18

text:
The latest Market Talks covering Equities. Published exclusively on Dow Jones Newswires throughout the day.

1028 ET - AB Foods reported a robust 1H with broad-based improvement across its portfolio despite Primark's volume remaining challenged, Barclays analysts Warren Ackerman and Patrick Folan say. The British conglomerate's standout figures were the 39% increase in adjusted operating profit and 46% rise in adjusted EPS, the analysts highlight. Despite the focus on Primark's margin beat, the strength of grocery, ingredients and sugar businesses was equally impressive, they say in a note. "Overall the results show a clear normalization of trends after the Covid years, supply chain challenges and inflation headwinds and the bounce back in profitability is a testament to the resilience of AB Foods' business model which some had questioned," they add. Barclays lifts the price target on the stock to GBP27 from GBP24. Shares are up 9.6%, and up 34% on a 12-month basis. (michael.susin@wsj.com)

1026 ET - Executive and board turnover at Tidewater Renewables increases investor risk, though that is mitigated by a positive update on the company's Renewable Diesel & Renewable Hydrogen Complex, CIBC Capital Markets' Robert Catellier says. The analyst says investors would understandably be nervous of a CFO departure, with Raymond Kwan set to be succeeded by Ian Quartly. Also, director John Adams has resigned due to potential future conflicts of interest with respect to his position. Still, Catellier says the operating update indicates the facility exceeded prior guidance for 1Q and is off to a good start for 2Q. He says this suggests operations ramped up more smoothly, improving financial liquidity and allowing the company to focus on free cash flow generation and debt reduction. (robb.stewart@wsj.com)

1001 ET - Holcim is expected to report lower sales later this week for its first quarter, according to consensus estimates provided by the Swiss building-material company. Analysts estimate revenue at CHF5.62 billion, which compares with CHF5.72 billion the same period the prior year. Recurring earnings before interest and taxes are forecast at CHF501 million, up from CHF493 million a year earlier. Shares trade 1.6% higher at CHF78.72. (nina.kienle@wsj.com)

0956 ET - UPS chief executive Carol Tomé says that the incoming air cargo volume from the U.S. Postal Service fits in with UPS' business-to-business network, and while it will hire additional pilots, UPS will not be buying more planes. UPS expects the onboarding to occur before peak season starts and expects more volume to be moved through UPS's regional gateways, rather than have that mostly funneled through UPS's world port in Louisville, Kentucky in a hub-and-spoke model. USPS has been diverting volume to its ground network to cut costs but UPS noted that there are minimum volume requirements in the contract. USPS recently picked UPS to move its air cargo, replacing FedEx. (esther.fung@wsj.com; @estherfung)

0916 ET - AI should factor more into Thomson Reuters business going forward, according to National Bank of Canada's Adam Shine in a report. The analyst says GenAI has been a focus of Reuters' disclosures and anchored its investor day in March where it noted that its "Big 3" [Legal, Tax and Accounting and News & Media] core segments generated $5.5 billion in revenue in 2023 out of total $26 billion market. The total addressable market is estimated at $71 billion, but with GenAI, this increases to $84 billion for a 7%-10% CAGR opportunity, Shine says. He thinks the "expectations [are] that customers will steadily spend more on products of Thomson Reuters and its peers to gain efficiencies as they potentially reduce headcount and their real estate footprint." (adriano.marchese@wsj.com)

0907 ET - Sales of Zyn, the viral cigarette alternative, soared to new heights in the latest quarter. Philip Morris International says it shipped 131.6 million cans of its Zyn nicotine pouches in the U.S. in 1Q, an increase of nearly 80% compared to the same period last year. Zyn's share of the U.S. nicotine pouch category increased for the fourth consecutive quarter to more than 74%, Philip Morris says. Zyn's volume growth contributed to the company's overall revenue increase of 11% excluding currency impacts and the impact of acquisitions, Philip Morris says. (jennifer.maloney@wsj.com)

0857 ET - Novartis eyes the expansion of its market presence in China and is on the look out to acquire further biotech companies, Chief Financial Officer Harry Kirsch says in a press call. The Swiss pharma major expects China to drive its business growth ahead of the forecasted 5% compound annual growth rate through 2028, Kirsch says. Novartis is set to acquire biotech companies at any given time with a focus on smaller M&As around up to $5 billion of deal size, bolstering the pipeline in its four key therapeutic areas, Kirsch adds. Shares rise 3.7% to CHF90.59. (helena.smolak@wsj.com)

0837 ET - Reckitt Benckiser's 1Q revenue is expected to fall as pricing eases and volumes are anticipated to return to growth after nearly two years of decreases, a company-compiled consensus shows. The London-listed company--which houses Dettol, Harpic and Durex among its brands--is expected to report revenue for the quarter of GBP3.70 billion, compared with GBP3.92 billion the same period a year ago. Net revenue growth is forecast to be 5.4%, comprising 3.2% growth in volumes and 2.2% in pricing, the consensus shows. This could mark the return to growth for Reckitt's volumes for the first time since the first half of 2022, when companies started to lift prices to pass on inflationary pressures to consumers, sacrificing their sales volumes. Shares are down 34% on a 12-month basis and down 21% on YTD basis. (michael.susin@wsj.com)

0828 ET - RTX says it's reached compensation deals with nine customers over the problems with its GTF engines that have grounded hundreds of Airbus aircraft. Spirit is one of the few to so far disclose a deal, and analysts expect settlements could cost RTX $2.5B this year. RTX didn't change its expectation that the issue could cost as much as $7B to rectify. CFO Neil Mitchill says talks continue with partners including MTU--RTX has 51% of the program--about their share of the bill. (doug.cameron@wsj.com)

0819 ET - GE Aerospace posted better-than-expected results for 1Q, which included the performance of the power business that it officially separated from days after the quarter ended. The standalone company that has emerged is now expecting to generate stronger profitability than it previously guided for. The company is now targeting an operating profit of $6.2 billion to $6.6 billion for 2024, up from previous guidance for $6 billion to $6.5 billion. CEO H. Lawrence Culp chalked the raised outlook up to a strong start to the year, during which its commercial engines & services business and its defense & propulsion technologies business drove double-digit growth in revenue and profit. GE Aerospace is up 4.5% in premarket trading. (dean.seal@wsj.com)

0817 ET - Reckitt Benckiser's disappointing fiscal 2023 performance and the U.S. litigation uncertainties have prompted shares to drop 23% year to date, meaning that such adversities are already firmly included in the stock price, Jefferies analysts say in a note. Added to that, the company's liability risk regarding its infant formula is likely to be reduced given the formal stance taken by necrotizing enterocolitis non-profit, the NEC Society last week, which said that a punitive legal outcome for Reckitt could have negative consequences for babies and eliminate potentially beneficial therapy choices, the analysts highlight. While uncertainties are likely to persist for the next 12 months, the skew to downside risk is firmly established in the price. Jefferies upgrades the stock to hold from underperfom and lifts price target to GBP44.00 from GBP41.00. (michael.susin@wsj.com)

0746 ET - GE Aerospace says it delivered 367 Leap jetliner engines in the latest quarter, one more than a year ago but down from 396 in the previous period. GE didn't break down deliveries between models used on Airbus and Boeing jets, but said availability of materials and supplier issues remain as it pushes to boost output by as much as 25% this year compared with 2023. Rival RTX didn't detail deliveries of its troubled GTF engine, though said sales in the quarter to aircraft makers had increased. (doug.cameron@wsj.com)

(END) Dow Jones Newswires

April 23, 2024 06:39 ET (10:39 GMT)
title: International Sugar Organization Prices - Apr 23

text:
1549 GMT - Coffee prices rise 1% to $2.06 a pound, gaining support from poor robusta coffee bean production in heat wave-stricken Vietnam. While production levels for the 2024-25 season are expected to provide a surplus, short-term prices could rise further to $2.10-$2.20 a pound due to adverse weather and further financial inflows, among other factors, Citi says. The U.S. bank hikes its 2024 average price expectation around 10% to $1.94 a pound. "To the extent robusta supply stays tight and consumption rebounds in 2025, the risk skew for higher coffee prices appears to have increased in [the second quarter]," Citi analysts say in a note. Elsewhere on the commodities market, cocoa futures fall 0.7% to $9,461 a ton, while sugar rises 0.6% to 22 cents a pound. (joseph.hoppe@wsj.com)

(END) Dow Jones Newswires

text:
1428 GMT - AB Foods reported a robust 1H with broad-based improvement across its portfolio despite Primark's volume remaining challenged, Barclays analysts Warren Ackerman and Patrick Folan say. The British conglomerate's standout figures were the 39% increase in adjusted operating profit and 46% rise in adjusted EPS, the analysts highlight. Despite the focus on Primark's margin beat, the strength of grocery, ingredients and sugar businesses was equally impressive, they say in a note. "Overall the results show a clear normalization of trends after the Covid years, supply chain challenges and inflation headwinds and the bounce back in profitability is a testament to the resilience of AB Foods' business model which some had questioned," they add. Barclays lifts the price target on the stock to GBP27 from GBP24. Shares are up 9.6%, and up 34% on a 12-month basis. (michael.susin@wsj.com)

April 22, 2024 13:46 ET (17:46 GMT)
title: ICE Europe Coffee,Cocoa,Sugar Volume and Open Interest - Apr 22

text:
By Michael Susin

AB Foods is scheduled to report results for the first half on Tuesday. Here is what you need to know.

REVENUE FORECAST: The British conglomerate is expected to report revenue of 9.90 billion pounds ($12.25 billion), according to a consensus taken from Visible Alpha and based on 13 analysts' estimates. This compares with GBP9.56 billion reported the same period a year ago.

PRIMARK REVENUE FORECAST: Sales at Primark--AB Foods' retail arm and biggest earnings contributor--are expected to increase to GBP4.54 billion, according to Visible Alpha, from GBP4.23 billion a year ago.

SUGAR REVENUE FORECAST: Sales of the sugar division are forecast to increase to GBP1.25 billion from GBP1.19 billion, according to the Visible Alpha consensus estimate.

Shares have risen by around 22% on a 12-month basis and are up 5.6% since the start of the year at GBP24.99.

WHAT TO WATCH

--Investors will look for any changes to AB Foods' guidance for fiscal 2024. The company expects Primark's adjusted operating profit margin, which strips out exceptional and other one-off items, to be above 10%. The improvement is supported by careful stock management, reduced input cost pressures and selective price increases, AJ Bell said in a note.

--Primark's progress in store openings will also be in focus, Liberum analysts Anubhav Malhotra and Wayne Brown said in a note. The company is also expected to comment on plans for the expansion of click-and-collect services to more stores and the development of the product portfolio, they added.

--The sugar division is expected to be the biggest driver of profit increase, AJ Bell wrote. Profit from the agriculture business is expected to rise, while the grocery segment profit is expected flat and the ingredients business is forecast slightly down owing to ongoing investment, AJ said.

Write to Michael Susin at michael.susin@wsj.com

(END) Dow Jones Newswires

1005 GMT - Cocoa prices rise, crossing the $10,000 a ton threshold for the third time this week on supply-crunch concerns. Cocoa futures rise 0.2% to $9,971 a ton, having reached as high as $10,044 earlier in the session and briefly hitting a record $10,324 a ton on Tuesday. The price has more than doubled in the year to date--as of March, cocoa beans are more expensive than copper--as inclement weather in West Africa and geographically constrained supply combine to cause the surge, HSBC analysts say in a note. Ghana--the world's second-largest supplier--could have its lowest harvest in more than two decades, according to its Cocoa Board, analysts from BMI Research, a unit of Fitch Solutions say in a note. Elsewhere, coffee gains 1.2% to $2 a pound, and sugar rises 0.9% to 23 cents a pound. (joseph.hoppe@wsj.com)

title: ICE Europe Coffee,Cocoa,Sugar Volume and Open Interest - Apr 18

text:
By Joe Hoppe

Food prices rose for the first time in seven months in March, as prices of vegetable oils, dairy products and meat more than offset lower sugar and cereal prices, the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations said on Friday.

The FAO's food price index, which tracks global prices for a basket of staple foods, averaged 118.3 points in March, up 1.1% from February's level and around 7.7% lower from a year earlier. In February, food prices fell 0.7% from the previous month.

Vegetable oil prices rose 8% in March, hitting a one-year high. This reflects an increase in price for palm, soy, sunflower and rapeseed oils. International palm oil prices rose on seasonally lower output and strong demand in Southeast Asia, while soy oil prices bounced back from multi-year lows on biofuel sector demand, according to the latest FAO report.

Dairy prices rose 2.9% from February levels, driven by increasing cheese and butter prices and marking the sixth consecutive monthly price rise, though it remains down 8.2% on year.

Meat prices rose by 1.7% in March, lifted by international prices for poultry, pig and bovine meats, and stand just 1.5% down on year.

Cereal prices, however, fell 2.6% in March, and are down 20% on year. This reflects lower prices for wheat on strong export competition among the European Union, Russia and the U.S. Maize prices, by contrast, edged up partially driven by Ukrainian logistical difficulties, the FAO said. Rice fell 1.7% on low global import demand. Cancelled wheat purchases by China placed further downward pressure, and prospects look good for the 2024 harvest in Russia and the U.S.

Sugar prices were up 5.4% from February's levels, due to an improvement in Indian sugar production forecasts and better harvest pace in Thailand.

text:
By Joe Hoppe

A roundup of key agricultural commodity markets for the week April 15-19 by Dow Jones Newswires in Barcelona.

GRAINS & OILSEEDS

:

The macro mood is bearish as the dollar climbed to new 2024 highs at the end of last week following a stronger-than-expected consumer price index print, a headwind for agriculture futures.

The U.S. dollar's rise has left crucial commodities currencies like the Australian and Canadian dollars, Chinese yuan and the Brazilian real weak.

South American weather looks good with no major threats, as Brazil enters the final stages of its soybean harvest and Argentina's harvest begins to ramp up into mid-April and early May, Peak Trading analysts said in a note. Weather for Brazil's corn harvest has also improved, though there is still a big spread in production estimates.

U.S. weather forecasts are cool and dry, with some storms in the eastern corn belt. There are some spots in Iowa and Kansas with low moisture, but otherwise there are few major threats to planting.

April is a critical month for both the Brazilian second corn crop and the risky U.S. spring planting weeks, making price seasonals over the month traditionally bullish. Traders will continue building a spring price risk premium as a result, Peak Trading said.

There is little in the way of important economic data, so the market will instead focus on new geopolitical risks in the Middle East and corporate earnings, Peak said.

There are mixed signals in terms of demand. While Russia is still delaying certificates for some of its biggest grain exporters and Brazil's cash base is firm, the U.S. posted poor corn export sales last week, and China cancelled some purchases. The U.S. Department of Agriculture also downgraded 2024 soybean exports estimates to 2.12 billion bushels, from 2.17 billion bushels.

Friday's commitment of traders report indicated hedge funds bought hogs and soybean meal, and sold cattle, sugar and cotton, with funds having massive short bets in U.S. wheat markets.

Chicago wheat futures are 1.3% down at $5.49 a bushel on Monday, while corn is down 1% at $4.31 a bushel. Soybean prices are 1% down at $11.625 a bushel.

SOFT COMMODITIES:

Cocoa prices remain close to all-time highs. The crop's price has more than doubled since the start of the year and risen 7.8% in the past week alone. The monthslong surge has been pushed by supply-side challenges in West Africa, where 70% of global cocoa is produced.

Other soft commodities are also rising on adverse weather. Arabica coffee closed at $2.25 a pound on Friday, its highest price since October 2022. It follows in the footsteps of robusta coffee, which is up 6.2% over the past week at $3,973 a ton--just short of its record $4,003 a ton.

Arabica, primarily produced in Brazil, and robusta, principally grown in Vietnam, have both seen prices jump as adverse weather hit crop size in both locations, driving down global stock levels, said Saxobank's head of commodity strategy, Ole Hansen, in a note.

The latest fortnightly report from Brazilian sugar-cane industry association Unica showed record sugar production in center-south Brazil. Cumulative sugar output for the region stands at 42.4 million tons, up 26% on-year and an all-time high for the region, ING analysts say in a note.

Cocoa is up 1.5% at $10,636 a metric ton, while sugar is down 0.6% at 20 cents a pound on Monday. Coffee is up 2.2% at $2.25 a pound.

April 18, 2024 08:57 ET (12:57 GMT)
title: ICE Agricultural Final Volume

text:
The latest Market Talks covering Equities. Published exclusively on Dow Jones Newswires throughout the day.

1028 ET - AB Foods reported a robust 1H with broad-based improvement across its portfolio despite Primark's volume remaining challenged, Barclays analysts Warren Ackerman and Patrick Folan say. The British conglomerate's standout figures were the 39% increase in adjusted operating profit and 46% rise in adjusted EPS, the analysts highlight. Despite the focus on Primark's margin beat, the strength of grocery, ingredients and sugar businesses was equally impressive, they say in a note. "Overall the results show a clear normalization of trends after the Covid years, supply chain challenges and inflation headwinds and the bounce back in profitability is a testament to the resilience of AB Foods' business model which some had questioned," they add. Barclays lifts the price target on the stock to GBP27 from GBP24. Shares are up 9.6%, and up 34% on a 12-month basis. (michael.susin@wsj.com)

1026 ET - Executive and board turnover at Tidewater Renewables increases investor risk, though that is mitigated by a positive update on the company's Renewable Diesel & Renewable Hydrogen Complex, CIBC Capital Markets' Robert Catellier says. The analyst says investors would understandably be nervous of a CFO departure, with Raymond Kwan set to be succeeded by Ian Quartly. Also, director John Adams has resigned due to potential future conflicts of interest with respect to his position. Still, Catellier says the operating update indicates the facility exceeded prior guidance for 1Q and is off to a good start for 2Q. He says this suggests operations ramped up more smoothly, improving financial liquidity and allowing the company to focus on free cash flow generation and debt reduction. (robb.stewart@wsj.com)

1001 ET - Holcim is expected to report lower sales later this week for its first quarter, according to consensus estimates provided by the Swiss building-material company. Analysts estimate revenue at CHF5.62 billion, which compares with CHF5.72 billion the same period the prior year. Recurring earnings before interest and taxes are forecast at CHF501 million, up from CHF493 million a year earlier. Shares trade 1.6% higher at CHF78.72. (nina.kienle@wsj.com)

0956 ET - UPS chief executive Carol Tomé says that the incoming air cargo volume from the U.S. Postal Service fits in with UPS' business-to-business network, and while it will hire additional pilots, UPS will not be buying more planes. UPS expects the onboarding to occur before peak season starts and expects more volume to be moved through UPS's regional gateways, rather than have that mostly funneled through UPS's world port in Louisville, Kentucky in a hub-and-spoke model. USPS has been diverting volume to its ground network to cut costs but UPS noted that there are minimum volume requirements in the contract. USPS recently picked UPS to move its air cargo, replacing FedEx. (esther.fung@wsj.com; @estherfung)

0916 ET - AI should factor more into Thomson Reuters business going forward, according to National Bank of Canada's Adam Shine in a report. The analyst says GenAI has been a focus of Reuters' disclosures and anchored its investor day in March where it noted that its "Big 3" [Legal, Tax and Accounting and News & Media] core segments generated $5.5 billion in revenue in 2023 out of total $26 billion market. The total addressable market is estimated at $71 billion, but with GenAI, this increases to $84 billion for a 7%-10% CAGR opportunity, Shine says. He thinks the "expectations [are] that customers will steadily spend more on products of Thomson Reuters and its peers to gain efficiencies as they potentially reduce headcount and their real estate footprint." (adriano.marchese@wsj.com)

0907 ET - Sales of Zyn, the viral cigarette alternative, soared to new heights in the latest quarter. Philip Morris International says it shipped 131.6 million cans of its Zyn nicotine pouches in the U.S. in 1Q, an increase of nearly 80% compared to the same period last year. Zyn's share of the U.S. nicotine pouch category increased for the fourth consecutive quarter to more than 74%, Philip Morris says. Zyn's volume growth contributed to the company's overall revenue increase of 11% excluding currency impacts and the impact of acquisitions, Philip Morris says. (jennifer.maloney@wsj.com)

0857 ET - Novartis eyes the expansion of its market presence in China and is on the look out to acquire further biotech companies, Chief Financial Officer Harry Kirsch says in a press call. The Swiss pharma major expects China to drive its business growth ahead of the forecasted 5% compound annual growth rate through 2028, Kirsch says. Novartis is set to acquire biotech companies at any given time with a focus on smaller M&As around up to $5 billion of deal size, bolstering the pipeline in its four key therapeutic areas, Kirsch adds. Shares rise 3.7% to CHF90.59. (helena.smolak@wsj.com)

0837 ET - Reckitt Benckiser's 1Q revenue is expected to fall as pricing eases and volumes are anticipated to return to growth after nearly two years of decreases, a company-compiled consensus shows. The London-listed company--which houses Dettol, Harpic and Durex among its brands--is expected to report revenue for the quarter of GBP3.70 billion, compared with GBP3.92 billion the same period a year ago. Net revenue growth is forecast to be 5.4%, comprising 3.2% growth in volumes and 2.2% in pricing, the consensus shows. This could mark the return to growth for Reckitt's volumes for the first time since the first half of 2022, when companies started to lift prices to pass on inflationary pressures to consumers, sacrificing their sales volumes. Shares are down 34% on a 12-month basis and down 21% on YTD basis. (michael.susin@wsj.com)

0828 ET - RTX says it's reached compensation deals with nine customers over the problems with its GTF engines that have grounded hundreds of Airbus aircraft. Spirit is one of the few to so far disclose a deal, and analysts expect settlements could cost RTX $2.5B this year. RTX didn't change its expectation that the issue could cost as much as $7B to rectify. CFO Neil Mitchill says talks continue with partners including MTU--RTX has 51% of the program--about their share of the bill. (doug.cameron@wsj.com)

0819 ET - GE Aerospace posted better-than-expected results for 1Q, which included the performance of the power business that it officially separated from days after the quarter ended. The standalone company that has emerged is now expecting to generate stronger profitability than it previously guided for. The company is now targeting an operating profit of $6.2 billion to $6.6 billion for 2024, up from previous guidance for $6 billion to $6.5 billion. CEO H. Lawrence Culp chalked the raised outlook up to a strong start to the year, during which its commercial engines & services business and its defense & propulsion technologies business drove double-digit growth in revenue and profit. GE Aerospace is up 4.5% in premarket trading. (dean.seal@wsj.com)

0817 ET - Reckitt Benckiser's disappointing fiscal 2023 performance and the U.S. litigation uncertainties have prompted shares to drop 23% year to date, meaning that such adversities are already firmly included in the stock price, Jefferies analysts say in a note. Added to that, the company's liability risk regarding its infant formula is likely to be reduced given the formal stance taken by necrotizing enterocolitis non-profit, the NEC Society last week, which said that a punitive legal outcome for Reckitt could have negative consequences for babies and eliminate potentially beneficial therapy choices, the analysts highlight. While uncertainties are likely to persist for the next 12 months, the skew to downside risk is firmly established in the price. Jefferies upgrades the stock to hold from underperfom and lifts price target to GBP44.00 from GBP41.00. (michael.susin@wsj.com)

0746 ET - GE Aerospace says it delivered 367 Leap jetliner engines in the latest quarter, one more than a year ago but down from 396 in the previous period. GE didn't break down deliveries between models used on Airbus and Boeing jets, but said availability of materials and supplier issues remain as it pushes to boost output by as much as 25% this year compared with 2023. Rival RTX didn't detail deliveries of its troubled GTF engine, though said sales in the quarter to aircraft makers had increased. (doug.cameron@wsj.com)

(END) Dow Jones Newswires

April 23, 2024 10:30 ET (14:30 GMT)
title: Global Equities Roundup: Market Talk

text:
By Joe Hoppe

A roundup of key agricultural commodity markets for the week April 29-May 3 by Dow Jones Newswires in Barcelona.

GRAINS & OILSEEDS:

The macro mood is positive as oil prices slip back, the Brazilian real gains against the U.S. dollar and global stock markets recover ahead of a busy week.

The U.S. dollar's rise had previously weakened crucial commodity currencies like the Australian and Canadian dollars, as well as the Chinese yuan. Crude strength also has a strong correlation with agricultural markets, particularly grains, as it is used throughout the agricultural process from fuel to fertilizer.

South American weather has been mixed, with Brazilian weather too hot ahead of May, a critical production month for soybeans. Argentina looks good over the next week for its own corn harvest, but there are still questions around the extent of the damage from leafhopper disease.

U.S. weather forecasts are warm and wet, with some large storm systems set to roll through the driest parts of the U.S. plains again this week. Farmers are planting quickly despite frequent showers--good for production prospects, but bearish for prices. While it is early in the spring planting season, traders are building a risk premium on crop prices and the market will be bullish until the June summer seasonal high, Peak Trading analysts said in a note.

Several key U.S. macroeconomic events are coming up, which could change the trajectory of the U.S. dollar, with the Federal Reserve monetary policy decision on Wednesday and U.S. nonfarm payroll data on Friday. Recent readings show progress curbing inflation has stalled, and the Fed isn't expected to cut interest rates on Wednesday, strengthening the dollar.

There are mixed signals in terms of demand. Brazil's soybean and Argentina's corn demand have been firming due to slow farmer selling and leafhopper disease, but China's import pace has stalled and the country has almost no business booked from the U.S., a bearish signal for U.S. futures, Peak Trading said.

Friday's commitment of traders report indicated hedge funds bought $1.8 billion of agricultural futures in aggregate last week, on geopolitical risks and growing weather concerns, mostly buying grains and selling sugar.

Chicago wheat futures are down 2.6% at $6.06 a bushel, while corn is down 0.9% at $4.46 a bushel. Soybean prices rise 0.1% at $11.78 a bushel.

SOFT COMMODITIES:

Cocoa prices are slipping back from the all-time high of $11,722 a ton, set on April 19. The crop's price has more than doubled since the start of the year though it has fallen 8% in the last week alone. The monthslong surge had been driven by supply-side challenges in West Africa, where 70% of global cocoa is produced.

Friday's commitment of traders report saw broad selling of cocoa from funds, with the net long being reduced to a 14-month low as traders continued to exit an increasingly disorderly market, Saxo Bank's head of commodity strategy, Ole Hansen said in a note.

Rains in West Africa have increased the outlook for the mid-season crop. The front contract showed signs of buying fatigue, so it only needed a spark to ignite a sell-off, Hansen said in emailed commentary.

That said, demand for cocoa hasn't fallen as much as expected, with global grindings--a key metric for gauging demand--dropping just 0.7% on-year in the first quarter of 2024. This offers additional support to high price levels, as the data suggests demand may be stronger than previously forecast, said BMI, a unit of Fitch Solutions, in a note.

Sugar prices have been subdued due to Brazil's strong supply and depreciated currency. Nonetheless, recent adverse weather conditions affecting Brazilian sugar production have led to a modest price recovery from a low of 19.3 cents a pound on April 17, BMI said.

Cocoa is down 9% at $9,640 a metric ton, while sugar is up 2.4% at 19.5 cents a pound. Coffee rises 1.7% at $2.28 a pound.

Write to Joe Hoppe at joseph.hoppe@wsj.com

(END) Dow Jones Newswires
